	<p>Flipping the solidified plaster upside-down, a kiln liquifies and drains the wax positive from the plaster negative. The plaster is placed in a sand pit for structural support and insulation before a crucible of melted bronze pours into the plaster funnel.<sup>5</sup> Once sufficiently cool, the plaster is removed from the pit and shocked in lukewarm water to compromise the material for easy dismantling.<sup>6</sup> Softening remaining plaster in water allows a wire brush to scrap and remove any cruft.<sup>7</sup> Angle grinders cut excess branches and roughly buff the bronze.<sup>8</sup> The piece is sand blasted to reach small, untouchable crevices and to texture it with a sparkling finish.<sup>9</sup></p>
